@NODE "Index" "DiskDataBase Index:"

   @{BOLD "DiskDataBase Index:"}
    
   @{" General Info      " LINK "Main"}
   
   @{" TroubleShooting   " LINK "TroubleShooting"} -- So ya think you got problems??
    
   @{" Menu Items        " LINK "MenuItems"}
    
   @{" Vanilla Keys      " LINK "VanillaKeys"} - Satanic KeyPresses

   @{" Author            " LINK "Author"} - Who wrote this great program?

   @{B}GADGETS:@{UB}
   @{" Artist Name " LINK "ArtistStringGad"} - Who are the Artists on the compact disc?
   @{" Disk Title  " LINK "DiskTitleString"} - What is the compact disc title?
   @{" Year        " LINK "YearIntegerGad"} - What is the copyright Year?

   @{" Disk Track Times " LINK "DiskTimesGad"} - Information from the compact disc about timing.
   @{" Track Titles     " LINK "TrackTitlesGad"} - What are the titles on the compact disc?

   @{" Read in CD " LINK "ReadInCDBUtton"} - Read the compact disc for track timing.
   @{" Load CD    " LINK "LoadCDButton"} - close the CDROM drive (with a compact disc in it).
   @{" EJECT!     " LINK "EjectButton"} - open the CDROM drive.

@ENDNODE

@TOC "Index"

@NODE "Main" "DiskDataBase General Information:"
@PREV "Index"
@TOC  "Index"

   @{BOLD "DiskDataBase General Information:"}

   A GUI for entering compact disc information into a DataBase.  Yes, it does not use
   MUI, reAction or BOOPSI, but given how many problems FreeDB has & that it does use
   MUI, I felt that the convenience of have a re-sizable GUI is just not worth the
   hassle of figuring out where the problems with MUI are located (just use the Zoom
   Gadget instead).

   The main reason for this program is that the FreeDB program that comes with AmigaOS4 has
   a lot of bugs in it.  After the last time it locked up my AmigaOne, I decided to just
   create a program that would read my CDs & allow me to enter the Track titles & other
   info by hand, then save it to the FreeDB:discs/ directories.
   @{FG SHINE}
   NOTE:  DiskDataBase does not necessarily produce entries that the freedb.org website 
          will accept.  The output does closely follow the directives that freedb.org
	  requests & names the output files in lowercase hexadecimal numbers (which FreeDB
	  does NOT!). @{FG TEXT}

   SEE ALSO, @{" ToolTypes " LINK "ToolTypes"}

  @{BOLD HISTORY}
       1.1 Fixed a minor bug (the program would exit if the drive specified was NOT a 
           CDROM, but was a DVD, DVD_CDRW or CDRW).
	   
       1.0 DiskDataBase is now working correctly!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "TroubleShooting" "Troubleshooting the Program:"
@PREV "Main"
@{FG SHINE}
   You're only going to find knowledge here, NOT Wisdom! @{FG TEXT}
   
   1. Make sure that the install script loaded any catalog files present to the correct
      location in your filing system.
      
   2. Make sure the Icon is in the same directory as the program.
   
   3. Make sure the Icon @{" ToolTypes " LINK "ToolTypes"} are configured correctly for your Amiga.
   
   4. If the program does something you don't understand, be sure to read the program 
      documentation completely!
      
   5. Send @{" me " LINK "Author"} an email describing your problem.       

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MenuItems" "PROJECT Menu Items:"
@PREV Main
@NEXT Index
   @{BOLD "PROJECT Menu Items:"}   

   Currently, these are the menu items available to the User of DiskDataBase:
   @{FG SHINE}
   PROJECT @{FG TEXT}
   Open..    -- Disabled until I figure out how to load in entries.
                @{FG SHINE}
		NOTE:  You MUST @{" Read In CD " LINK "ReadInCDButton"} BEFORE using the save menuItems! @{FG TEXT}
   Save      -- Save your compact disc information into the selected FreeDB:Discs/ directory. 
   Save To.. -- Save your compact disc information into the selected directory. @{FG SHINE}
                This is necessary since PlayCD does NOT know anything about the FreeDB:Discs/
		sub-directories! @{FG TEXT}
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   About -- This item displays a brief informative message about the DiskDataBase program.

   Help  -- This item should display this amigaguide file to you.  If it does not,
            then check the @{" HelpViewer " LINK "ToolTypes"} ToolType for a correct
	    program that displays amigaguide files & that you have DiskDataBase.guide
	    (but then, you must have it or you wouldn't be reading this!)
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   Quit  -- This item simply exits the DiskDataBase program (after checking your sanity, which
            the Close Window Gadget will not do!).

   See Also, @{" Vanilla Keys " LINK "VanillaKeys"}
   
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ToolTypes" "ToolTypes recognized by DiskDataBase:"
@PREV "Main"

   @{B}ToolTypes used by DiskDataBase:@{UB}
@{FG SHINE}
       ToolType:               Default Value:             NOTES:
       ~~~~~~~~~               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~             ~~~~~~ @{FG TEXT}
       DeviceName            = a1ide.device               (Should not have to change this!)
       UNitNumber            = 1                          (Change to your CDROM device number)
       DBasePathName         = FreeDB:Discs               (Where your disk information will be stored)
       HelpViewer            = System:Utilities/MultiView (Something that can display amigaguide files)
       HelpFile              = DiskDataBase.guide         (The name of this file!)
      
@ENDNODE

@NODE "LoadCDButton" "Load CD Button Gadget:"
@PREV "Main"
@NEXT "EjectButton"

   When you've placed another compact disc in the drive tray, you can have the program 
   load it in the drive by clicking on this Button.

   SEE ALSO, @{" EJECT! " LINK "EjectButton"} - Button Gadget

@ENDNODE

@NODE "EjectButton" "Eject Button Gadget:"
@PREV "LoadCDButton"
@NEXT "Main"

   When you're done with a compact disc, you can have the program eject the disc for you by
   clicking on this Button.

   SEE ALSO, @{" Load CD " LINK "LoadCDButton"} - Button Gadget

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ArtistStringGad" "compact disc Artist Name:"
@PREV "Main"
@NEXT "DiskTitleString"

   Enter the name of the Artist that created the compact disc.  The disc will tell you who that
   might be (you can read can't you?)

   SEE ALSO, @{" Disk Title: " LINK "DiskTitleString"}   

@ENDNODE

@NODE "DiskTitleString" "compact disc Title:"
@PREV "ArtistStringGad"
@NEXT "YearIntegerGad"

   Enter the name of the compact disc.  The disc will tell you what that
   might be (you can read can't you?)

   SEE ALSO, @{" Year: " LINK "YearIntegerGad"}   

@ENDNODE

@NODE "YearIntegerGad" "Year Integer Gadget:"
@PREV "DiskTitleString"
@NEXT "Main"

   Enter the year the compact disc was CopyRight'ed 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "DiskTimesGad" "Disk Times Gadget:"

   This Gadget will display the timing information of the compact disc in the following
   format:
   
   track #: Frame Offset #; # minutes; # seconds; # frames

   This is a read-only gadget.   

@ENDNODE

@NODE "TrackTitlesGad" "Track Titles Gadget:"

   You enter the titles of the tracks present on the compact disc by first clicking on the
   first empty slot beneath the title description string.
   This will activate the string gadget directly beneath the @{B}Track Titles@{UB} Gadget.
   
   Once you've entered a title & pressed the <RETURN>/ENTER key on your keyboard, your new
   title will be moved into the @{B}Track Titles@{UB} Gadget & the string Gadget will be cleared
   & activated for the next title you want to enter (if any).  I've tried to make the
   process of entering the track titles as painless as possible, since this is where you're
   going to be spending the most time in the program.
   
@ENDNODE

@NODE "ReadInCDBUtton" "Run as Device Button:"
@{FG SHINE}
   WARNING:  You must have a disk in the CDROM drive BEFORE you click on this button,
             otherwise there's nothing in the drive for the program to read in! @{FG TEXT}
   
   This button will read the compact disc for timing information & compute the name of the 
   compact disc.  This name is a 32-bit hexadecimal number, which is used by PlayCD &
   freedb.org when referring to the compact disc.  This ID number is computed with the
   algorithm recommended by freedb.org.  This ID number must be computed before you try
   to use the @{" Save " LINK "MenuItems"} or @{" Save To.. " LINK "MenuItems"} menu Items.
   		
@ENDNODE

@NODE "VanillaKeys" "Keys that DiskDataBase recognizes:"
@PREV "Main"

  The intent is to keep your hands on the keyboard instead of constantly switching back & forth
  between the mouse & the keyboard.
      
  @{SHINE "a or A:"}Same as activating the @{" Artist Name " LINK "ArtistStringGad"} String Gadget.

  @{SHINE "d or D:"}Same as activating the @{" Disk Title  " LINK "DiskTitleString"} String Gadget.

  @{SHINE "e or E:"}Same as pressing the @{" EJECT!      " LINK "EjectButton"} Button.

  @{SHINE "l or L:"}Same as pressing the @{" Load CD     " LINK "LoadCDButton"} Button.

  @{SHINE "r or R:"}Same as pressing the @{" Read in CD  " LINK "ReadInCDButton"} Button.
    
  @{SHINE "y or Y:"}Same as activating the @{" Year        " LINK "YearIntegerGad"} Button.

  PROJECT MenuItems:
  @{SHINE "i or I:"}Shows an Information requester.
  @{SHINE "h or H:"}Display the DiskDataBase.guide file (which you are now reading!)
  @{SHINE "o or O:"}Load in some compact disc information (currently disabled).  
  @{SHINE "q or Q:"}Alternative exit point for the DiskDataBase program.
  @{SHINE "s or S:"}Save your compact disc information.
  @{SHINE "t or T:"}Save your compact disc information to a directory of your choosing.

@ENDNODE

